# /usr/culture/languages/
# ~7,000 living languages. One dying every two weeks.
# Each language is a unique way of parsing reality.
#
# The Sapir-Whorf hypothesis (weak form): language influences thought.
# Speakers of languages with absolute spatial terms (east/west)
# have better spatial orientation than speakers using relative terms (left/right).
# Time flows left-to-right for English speakers, right-to-left for Arabic speakers.
# The Pirahã language has no numbers — and its speakers cannot
# perform exact quantity matching.
#
# Every language that dies takes a way of seeing with it.
# The extinction rate exceeds species extinction.
#
# Top 10 by native speakers:
#   1. Mandarin Chinese  (~920M)
#   2. Spanish           (~475M)
#   3. English           (~373M)
#   4. Arabic            (~362M)
#   5. Hindi             (~344M)
#   6. Bengali           (~234M)
#   7. Portuguese        (~232M)
#   8. Russian           (~154M)
#   9. Japanese          (~125M)
#  10. Punjabi           (~118M)
#
# But English is the lingua franca of science, aviation,
# diplomacy, and the internet — not because it is superior
# but because of historical power dynamics (colonialism, Hollywood, Silicon Valley).
# Languages spread by power, not by merit.
